LAUSANNE - The Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS) has slapped a lifetime ban on a Russian doctor for using prohibitive substances on athletes.READ: Phelps urges US lawmakers to push for anti-doping reformIn a statement CAS said it had issued its decision in the arbitration procedure between the International Association of Athletics Federation (IAAF), the Russian Athletics Federation (RusAF) and Dr Sergei Portugalov, a Russian medical doctor who advised athletes affiliated to RusAF.On the basis of clear evidence, Dr Portugalov is found to have violated the following articles of the IAAF Anti-Doping and Medical Rules: Article 32.2(f) ( Possession of a Prohibited Substance or Prohibited Method ), Article 32.2(g) ( Trafficking or Attempted Trafficking in any Prohibited Substance or Prohibited Method ) and Article 32.2(h) ( Administration or Attempted Administration of a Prohibited Substance or Prohibited Method ).READ: Crucial Team Sky medical records 'stolen': UK anti-doping chiefAs a consequence, a lifetime period of ineligibility, beginning on March 10, 2017, has been imposed on Dr Portugalov.READ: Fredericks quits 2024 Olympics role, denies wrongdoingThe CAS acted as first instance decision-making authority for this matter, substituting for RusAF, which was suspended at the time the matter was ready to be adjudicated (and which remains suspended). African News Agency